  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>For a long time, energy efficiency was treated as an afterthought in Australian residential property. Buyers focused on layout, location, and condition. Energy bills were assumed to be a problem you only really thought about after settling in. That is changing. In Brisbane, where summer cooling loads dominate household energy use, the cost of running a poorly designed home is increasingly visible to buyers, and the cost of running a well-designed one is increasingly attractive. Sellers who understand how energy performance is judged, how to evidence it, and what to invest in (and what not to invest in) before listing produce stronger results.</p>

      <p>This article walks through what NatHERS actually measures, when a rating applies, how Brisbane buyers respond to energy features today, what improvements pay off at sale, and how to disclose the property's energy performance honestly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What NatHERS is</h2>
      <p>NatHERS is the Nationwide House Energy Rating Scheme. It is a 0 to 10 star rating that measures a home's thermal performance, which is the home's ability to keep occupants comfortable without relying heavily on heating or cooling. The rating is generated using accredited modelling software, based on the home's insulation levels, glazing performance, orientation to the sun, building envelope sealing, and thermal mass. A higher star rating means a home that is cheaper and more comfortable to live in across the year. New homes built since 2003 typically have a NatHERS rating from construction. Significant renovations involving changes to the building envelope can also generate a rating. Older Brisbane homes generally do not have a formal NatHERS rating.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When a NatHERS rating applies</h2>
      <p>NatHERS ratings apply formally to new builds completed under the relevant National Construction Code provisions, to major renovations where the building approval required energy compliance, and to any property that has voluntarily had a rating assessment commissioned. Most existing inner Brisbane homes, particularly anything built before 2003 or any older Queenslander, will not have a rating. The absence of a rating is not a defect, but the presence of a strong rating is increasingly a marketing asset for newer or substantially renovated properties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The buyer perception spectrum</h2>
      <p>Different buyer pools weight energy efficiency differently. Younger buyers, particularly under forty, increasingly prioritise energy efficiency for both cost and values reasons. Investor buyers value lower running costs because they support stronger rental yields and reduced tenant complaints. Older buyers and downsizers tend to prioritise it less in headline terms, but they still respond positively to lower bills and to homes that stay comfortable without heavy reliance on air conditioning. Family buyers occupy the middle of the spectrum, often valuing efficiency once they understand the long-term impact on monthly outgoings. The practical lesson is that energy efficiency is rarely the single feature that closes the deal, but it is increasingly the feature that wins on a tie-breaker between two otherwise similar homes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives energy performance in Brisbane</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's subtropical climate means summer cooling is the dominant load. The features that matter most are ceiling insulation, which is by far the highest impact and lowest cost improvement available; effective glazing, with double or low-e glass uncommon in older homes but increasingly standard in new builds; northerly orientation with appropriate eave depth, which delivers passive solar warmth in winter and shade in summer; ceiling fans and natural cross-ventilation, which are essential in any Brisbane home; and quality wall and underfloor insulation, particularly in elevated Queenslanders where the underfloor air gap can become a major source of summer heat gain. Each of these features either reduces the cooling load or makes air conditioning more effective when it is used.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Easy improvements before listing</h2>
      <p>The improvements that pay back most reliably at sale are the cheap ones. Adding ceiling insulation if it is missing typically costs $1,500 to $3,500 for an average inner Brisbane home and makes a measurable difference to summer comfort and energy bills. Installing or upgrading ceiling fans in major rooms costs $300 to $600 each installed and is among the most positively received features by Brisbane buyers, who instinctively understand the value of moving air. Adding window furnishings such as quality curtains and blinds reduces summer heat gain and is cheap to do. Servicing existing air conditioning so that it runs cleanly and efficiently costs $150 to $250 per unit and removes a common buyer concern at the inspection stage.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bigger improvements and their honest ROI</h2>
      <p>The more expensive efficiency improvements have less reliable returns. Replacing single-glazed windows with double-glazed units typically costs $800 to $1,500 per window and is rarely recouped in full at sale unless the property is targeting a specifically efficiency-conscious buyer pool. Adding solar PV is a different case: a quality system in the 6 to 10 kilowatt range typically pays back through a combination of reduced bills during ownership and a positive sale-price impact, particularly if the system has battery storage and the documentation is clean. Improving underfloor insulation in elevated Queenslanders is worth doing if the home is being substantially renovated, but standalone retrofits rarely pay back at sale. The general rule is that improvements that beat the buyer's expectations work best, and improvements that simply meet the buyer's expectations are taken for granted.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to disclose and how</h2>
      <p>The most powerful energy disclosure tool is real, recent data. Provide the most recent twelve months of electricity bills (and gas, if applicable) on request. Buyers value transparency more than they value claims. If the property has any NatHERS rating certificates, solar PV installation paperwork, battery storage details, or smart energy management system records, compile them into the property pack alongside the building documentation. If recent improvements have been made (insulation, fans, glazing) keep the receipts and scope-of-works documents so that the upgrades can be substantiated. Buyer lenders are increasingly interested in evidence-based energy claims, particularly for green loan products that may be available to the buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The marketing angle</h2>
      <p>For energy-conscious buyers, specific features anchor better than generic claims. "Ducted reverse-cycle air conditioning", "fully insulated ceilings and walls", "north-facing aspect with deep eaves", "10kW solar with 13kWh battery storage" are phrases that set expectations precisely and that hold up when the buyer's inspector arrives. Vague phrases such as "energy efficient" or "environmentally friendly" without supporting features are easily dismissed and can even create suspicion. The marketing pack should include the most recent annual energy bill on request, alongside any installation certificates and warranty documents.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <p>Do not claim energy efficiency benefits without supporting evidence, since unsupported claims are easily picked apart at inspection and damage seller credibility. Do not estimate annual savings from past improvements without documentation, because the buyer's lender or solicitor may want substantiation for any number put into marketing material. Do not over-invest in expensive efficiency upgrades hoping they will produce a clean dollar-for-dollar return at sale, because the evidence does not support it for most properties. The exception is solar PV with proper documentation, which generally pays back at sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The regulatory direction</h2>
      <p>Australia is moving toward mandatory energy performance disclosure for residential property sales. The ACT already requires Energy Efficiency Rating disclosure on listing. Queensland is widely expected to follow within the next decade as part of the national push toward decarbonisation. Sellers who think about energy performance now, and who treat documentation as part of standard property records, will be well placed for whatever disclosure regime eventually applies. There is also a quieter advantage in being an early-mover: buyers who care about efficiency notice when a seller has clearly prepared, and that preparation lifts the perceived quality of the property as a whole.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical framework</h2>
      <p>Treat energy efficiency as a meaningful enhancement, not a primary selling point. Make the easy improvements (insulation, fans, window furnishings, AC servicing) before listing because they pay back reliably in buyer perception. Avoid major retrofits unless the property is targeting a specifically efficiency-focused buyer pool. Provide real data (recent energy bills, installation certificates) rather than vague claims. Mention specific features in marketing copy, not generic descriptors. The goal is to remove energy concerns from the buyer's list of objections rather than to chase a premium based on efficiency alone. Done well, this produces a smoother campaign, a more confident buyer pool, and a stronger price.</p>

